fi Paulum. L. Aemilius Paulus, sumamed Macedonicus from his victory over Perseus, died in B.c. 160, that is, thirty-one years before the time at which Laelius is supposed to be speaking. He was consul for the first time in B. c. 182, and ‚for the second in nc. 168. He was

. theson of the consul who died at Cannae and the father of the younger Africanus. He lost his two younger sons, one four days before his triumph over Perseus, the other three days after. Their death was the more lamentablc,¹ as his two elder sons, Q. Fabius Maximus Aemilianus and P. Cornelius Scipio Aemilianus, had been lost to his house by adoption, and there was no one to carry on the line. The praise of his magnanimity, which is so frequent in Cicero’s mouth (cp. Ad Fam. IV, 6, 5 1), seems to be based on a speech which he delivered to the people, of which a notable passage has been· preserved by Valerius Maximus (V, 10, ξ 2).
